choice_meaningfulness (scene-scale, quest-only): The input is a FULL SCENE
(2000-4000 words) ending in a voter choice. Score how far the options
diverge in *consequence* — not just flavor. Judge the whole scene, not the
choice text in isolation; the scene should have set up why each branch
matters.

0.0 = options collapse to the same future: wording differs, outcomes do
      not. Pure flavor. No stake traded against another.
0.3 = options differ in minor tactical detail but converge on the same
      world-state within the next update.
0.5 = options diverge in at least one tangible thread (an NPC relationship,
      a resource, a goal) but share the same overall trajectory.
0.7 = each option commits the protagonist to a distinct path with its own
      costs; the scene has earned the weight of each branch.
1.0 = each option is a visibly different world: different allies, different
      threats, different themes foregrounded. A voter cannot pick one and
      get another for free.

Anchors:
  HIGH: scene ends offering (a) break the oath and save the child, (b) keep
        the oath and let the faction live, (c) flee the city — each option
        rewrites the next arc.
  MID : scene ends offering "sneak in through the window" vs "sneak in
        through the cellar"; same heist, same outcome, different vibe.
  LOW : scene ends offering "say yes kindly" vs "say yes firmly"; the yes
        is load-bearing, the tone is not.
